meta-piracer
============

Hardware enablement snippets for the DES PiRacer controller stack. This layer
complements the head-unit/image layers by packaging runtime helpers that live
outside of Poky.

Provided recipes
----------------

* ``recipes-support/can/can1.bb`` – one-shot systemd unit that configures the
  ``can1`` SocketCAN interface at 500 kbit/s and keeps it up for the runtime.
* ``recipes-support/piracer-controller/piracer-controller.bb`` – installs the
  gamepad-to-vehicle bridge (`controller.py`, `gamepads.py`) and a
  ``piracer-controller.service`` unit that runs it at boot.
* ``recipes-python/vehicles/des-piracer-vehicles.bb`` – installs the vendor
  ``vehicles.py`` module into Python site-packages so the controller can drive
  the PiRacer hardware.

External dependencies
---------------------

* The controller script expects a ``vehicles`` module that exposes the
  ``PiRacerStandard`` class. Point ``VEHICLES_SRC`` (in
  ``des-piracer-vehicles.bb``) to your vendor SDK path (e.g.
  ``${TOPDIR}/../../DES_PiRacer-Assembly/piracer``). If missing, the controller
  still runs in a stub mode and logs a warning.
* A compliant USB gamepad must appear as ``/dev/input/js0``.

Integration
-----------

Add the layer to your build:

.. code-block:: bash

   bitbake-layers add-layer meta-custom/meta-piracer

Then extend your image recipe to include the packages:

.. code-block:: bitbake

   IMAGE_INSTALL:append = " can1 piracer-controller "

At runtime, confirm the services:

* ``systemctl status can1``
* ``systemctl status piracer-controller``

For debugging or bench testing without hardware the controller logs to the
journal; once the vendor ``vehicles`` module is present it will drive the ESC
and steering servos as expected.
